In mathematics, an '''idempotent [[binary relation]]''' ''R''&nbsp;⊆&nbsp;''X''&nbsp;[[Cartesian product|×]]&nbsp;''X'' is one for which ''R''&nbsp;[[Relation composition|∘]]&nbsp;''R''&nbsp;=&nbsp;''R''.<ref>{{cite techreport| author=Florian Kammüller, J. W. Sanders| title=Idempotent Relation in Isabelle/HOL| year=2004| number=2004-04| pages=27| institution=TU Berlin| url=http://cs.tu-berlin.de/cs/ifb/Ahmed/RoteReihe/2004/TR2004_04.pdf}} Here:p.3</ref><ref>{{cite article| author=Florian Kammüller| title=Mechanical Analysis of Finite Idempotent Relations| year=2011|journal=Fundamenta Informaticae|volume=107|pages=43–65|DOI=10.3233/FI-2011-392}}</ref> This notion generalizes that of an [[idempotent function]] to relations. Each idempotent relation is necessarily [[transitive relation|transitive]], as the latter means&nbsp;''R''&nbsp;∘&nbsp;''R''&nbsp;⊆&nbsp;''R''.

For example, the relation&nbsp;< on [[rational number|ℚ]] is idempotent. In contrast,&nbsp;<&nbsp;on [[integer number|ℤ]] is not, since (<)&nbsp;∘&nbsp;(<)&nbsp;[[Superset|⊇]]&nbsp;(<) does not hold: e.g. 1&nbsp;<&nbsp;2, but 1&nbsp;<&nbsp;''x''&nbsp;<&nbsp;2 is false for every&nbsp;''x''&nbsp;∈&nbsp;ℤ.

Idempotent relations have been used as an example to illustrate the application of Mechanized Formalisation
of mathematics using the interactive theorem prover Isabelle/HOL. Besides checking the mathematical properties of finite idempotent relations, an algorithm for counting the number of idempotent relations has been derived in Isabelle/HOL.
<ref>{{cite article| author=Florian Kammüller| title=Number of idempotent relations on n labeled elements|year=2006|journal=The On-Line Ecyclopedea of Integer Sequences|number=A12137|url=https://oeis.org/search?q=11%2C123%2C2360&sort=&language=english&go=Search}}</ref><ref>{{cite techreport| author=Florian Kammüller| title=Counting Idempotent Relations| year=2008| number=2008-15| pages=27| institution=TU Berlin| url=http://www.eecs.tu-berlin.de/fileadmin/f4/TechReports/2008/2008-15.pdf}}</ref>

